==English==
===Etymology===
From German ''[[#German|Verfredungseffekt]]''.
===Noun===
{{en-noun|Verfremdungseffekt|Verfremdungseffekte}}
# [[w:Brecht|Brecht's]] [[alienation]] [[effect]], sometimes translated as the [[estrangement]] effect.
#{{theater}} [[distance|Distance]] between the audience and the performers.
====Quotations====
*'''1997''' Clive Barker, Simon Trussler ''New Theatre Quarterly 50''
*:" Brecht's famous '''Verfremdungseffekte''' or "alienation effect", intended to counter the magical associations of stage illusion and the tendency for spellbound audiences to identify emotionally with characters on stage, both of which both of which Brecht found abhorrent." [http://books.google.com/books?ie=UTF-8&vid=ISBN0521589010&id=oeC5PIcm8mcC&pg=PA114&lpg=PA114&dq=verfremdungseffekte&vq=verfremdungseffekte&sig=lB1ePAvq52y9yYTA1iNlUq0o0tc]
